    <segment id="1" parent="27" relname="span">
        The consequences of adopting a pose of methodological relativism
IMHO are pretty profound.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="25" relname="span">  What if working scientists give up their
&quot;naive&quot; beliefs in academic freedom, shared community of knowledge, priority
of discovery and so forth.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="21" relname="span">  In other words, what happens to science if
STS succeeds in convincing scientists that the STS view of science is correct?</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration">
Never mind the consequences to science if STSers convince policymakers that
&quot;scientists are just making it up as they go along.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="concession">
        Gregor Mendel worked out the principles of Mendelian genetics in the
1860s</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span"> but his discoveries remained dormant until the turn of the century
when tow researchers independently disovered Mendel&apos;s rules and then
rediscovered Mendel.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="span">  Now genetics bears Mendel&apos;s name.....</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span">but imagine if
the two researchers were methodological relativsts.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="18" relname="span">  They &quot;know&quot; that there
is no reality out there,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> or it is inaccessible or whatever (depending on
which flavor of relativism you prefer).</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="solutionhood">  What is the thing for them to do?</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="19" relname="span">
Why *suppress* Mendel&apos;s work, fight each other, not share their research in
order to grab all the prestige, research funds etc. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="means"> Imagine a scientific
world of the struggle of all against all,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="22" relname="span"> and you have the world of
methodlogical relativism.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="elaboration">
        Principles like democracy and academic freedom, the shared community
of researchers, transmission of knowledge across national borders, the
recognition of priority of research and so forth, are these not incompatible 
with a position of methodological relativism?</segment>
